If GOR cannot be determined from the available data, the rule specifies that one of the procedures specified in paragraph (g)(1)(vii)(A) or (B) of this section must be used to determine GOR. If GOR from each well is not available, the GOR from a cluster of wells in the same sub-basin category should be used. Therefore, facilities have the option to use procedures specified in paragraph (g)(1)(vii)(A) or (B) to determine GOR, or use the GOR from a cluster of wells in the same sub-basin category if GOR from each well is not available.{
    "result": "To determine GOR for associated gas venting and flaring when a facility does not have a GOR value for a well, facilities can consider the following options: 1) Estimate GOR based on historical data from similar wells in the same area. 2) Use reservoir engineering techniques to estimate GOR based on reservoir pressure, temperature, and fluid properties. 3) Conduct a well test to directly measure the GOR. 4) Utilize empirical correlations or predictive models based on well characteristics and production data to estimate GOR. It's important to ensure that the chosen method aligns with industry best practices and regulatory requirements."
